ow German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Norbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from any of various places so named, for example in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Shropshire, Staffordshire, and Surrey, so called from Old English <i>north</i> ‘north’ + <i>burh</i> ‘fortress, fortified town’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Norbury was born about 1171, in Denchworth, Berkshire, England. She married Mathew de la Hyde about 1188. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died about 1196, at the age of 27."},"et":{"about 1171–about 1196":"umbes 1171–umbes 1196","1167–1211":"1167–1211","1188–Male":"1188–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1193–1236":"1193–1236","1195–Male":"1195–Su